Finding Sales Patterns in a Store



A retail analyst in Chennai tracks daily profit/loss values in an array. They want to find how many continuous periods (subarrays) have a total profit equal to a target value k.



Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the total number of subarrays whose sum equals k.



NOTE: A subarray is a contiguous sequence of elements.

Input format :
First line: integer n (size of the array)
Second line: n space-separated integers
Third line: integer k
Output format :
First line: Count: x (No. of Subarrays)
Code constraints :
1 <= n <= 2 * 10^4
-1000 <= nums[i] <= 1000
-10^7 <= k <= 10^7
Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3
1 1 1
2
Output 1 :
Count: 2
Input 2 :
5
1 2 3 -2 5
5
Output 2 :
Count: 2



Solution:


#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {

    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<int> nums(n);

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    int k;
    cin >> k;

    unordered_map<int,int> mp;

    mp[0] = 1;

    int sum = 0;
    int count = 0;

    for(int x : nums) {

        sum += x;

        if(mp.find(sum - k) != mp.end()) {
            count += mp[sum - k];
        }

        mp[sum]++;
    }

    cout << "Count: " << count;

    return 0;
}
